value.0: You can have a pet here.
Yes. Go check out a Pet Shop in a city and you can buy one.
Well....help you. They are not a Summons or a Familiar....they are your Pet. They will help you fight and just be there for you.
Horses will allow you to travel throughout the realms much faster.
You bet! NWNv1.69 comes with them. DLA (Dragonlance Adventures) introduced them with Wyvern Crown as a Bioware Premium Module. Now they are part of the Bioware update.
Well since Haste is only a Spell or Potion here travelling the world will take more time.
Yes. They also provide you with some security by allowing you to run away from tough enemies.
Horse combat as well as having your henchmen mount them as well.
There is a VERY good Horse Tutorial on the Neverwinter Vault (Google It). Search For Riding Academy. Or even easier.....download it from the Forum. The Link is Provided.
A Horse Merchant in a city or town. Some towns don't have horse merchants.
Yes. Almost forgot. You MUST have Ride Horse Skills to be able to Ride a Horse. Actually to even Purchase one you will be required to have the skill point. Just 1 skill point is enough.
Soon as you level up it will be available.
Some races do get the Feat and Skill for free....some do not. It all depends upon how you 'grew up'.
Pack Animals are a very much needed helper in this world. Ore and Wood are heavy.
Yes. You can place whatever else you want in the Pack Box too.
Sort of. Each Pack Animal can only carry so much.....you know....size and strength of the animal.

Well....this value is configurable by the Designer so it can vary. Maximum is 100 but it could be anywhere in between. Once you palce an item in the Pack Box for that Animal you will know how much you can stuff in it.
See an Animal Merchant in a city/town for available choices.
Well....really weird things. There are protection mechanisms in there so all should be good.
Well....databases are not 100% reliable. So....only keep really valuable things on your character. Like in your Back Pack and Boxes. It is YOUR risk to place things into the Pack Animals.

Yes. Of course. A recommendation.....only put Ores and Woods and other things you are collecting for Contracts and Bounties in the Pack Box. That way you will not lose Quest Items and other nice gear.
You can do some fishing in this world.
That is for you to find out. There are 3 types of water to fish from though.
Streams and Rivers, Lakes, and the Salt Waters.
Yes. The Salt waters you can even catch Crab and Lobster.
Indeed. Cook them in an Oven or on the Campfire.
Fishing is Dexterity and Wisdom based. So to catch fish effectively you need some abilities in these traits.
Nobody said it would be fair. It is realistic. There are a great many things that you will be able to do that others can not.
As long as you have a score of 10 you will have a chance.
With a score of 10 you may have to try a little longer.
You will need Food and Drink to survive in the world.
Good question. Yes. You can hunt animals and harvest foods in the wilds and purchase the goods in the nearest mercantile. You can also become intoxicated from drinking various alcoholic drinks.
Indeed. Just drink beer, whiskey, vodka....and many many others available aroud the realms. Once you start drinking them, depending upon your constitution, you will become intoxicated.
Well....if you drink enough....you will pass out!
Not really.....I am a code junky.
Yes. To eat it you will have to roast it though.
Cook them in an Oven or on the Campfire.
As long as you have Fresh meat or fish on you just click on the campfire.
There will be an option to set up the Cook Spit. Choose that.
Yes. Then simply place one of your Fresh meats or fish on the Cook Spit.
If your Wisdom score is 14 or below you will burn a lot of food.
These are in flats and houses.
You can rent an Inn Room or Purchase a House or Flat to also rest.
This depends a lot upon how you choose to adventure.
The heavier your armor and your inventory the faster you will tire.
Not really but it does help. You will just need to drink and eat more.
With a medium heavy invenory and medium armor you can expect to eat 2 times in 8 hours. Again, this is very subjective because everything you do affects this.
Yes. Even carrying your weapons and wearing your helm affects this.
You rest while you are traveling about in either Inns and houses or with your Tent or Bedroll.

Yes. You build a Campfire with Dry Wood from dead trees and light it with a Torch or Lantern. You will have to have a little Lore Skill to Spot the Dead Trees....pretty easy to do. You can also purchase Dry Wood at the local General Store.
You can rent an Inn Room or Purchase a House or Flat to also rest.
Yes. The rules on House Purchases are very particular though. You should make sure you join the forum to see the rules regarding this.
See the Captain of the guard or Sheriff for local city information. Many NPCs have information and quests and even sometimes just humor. Speak to many.
Yes and more. There are also bulletin boards around that have planned groups for an adventure.
Quests will be given out by many. The quests can be simple or multi-staged long term quests.
Yes. Some quests will take you many levels to be able to complete. You will need the help of friends to complete a great many of these.
Not in the sense you are thinking. Quests are individual......but if you and a friend can help each other out to complete the quest.
Coin will be rewarded as well....but only for you.....you will be removed from a party to finish your quest.
Sure it is. Each person can complete the quest and help each other get them done. Creatures and treasure respawn so all is needed is time.
Excellent. It is a very fair method.
Here you must find a Trainer to Level up.
Because it is the way things must be. It is a very important part of Role Playing your Character.
They can be found in the Guard Tower in each City. Each Trainer has their own capabilities though.
Well....let's say you are a Level 8 Fighter and are about to level up to Level 9. The local fighter trainer would have to have at least Level 9 to be able to train you.
You have to ask of course.
Ummm....how would you know in Real Life whether someone taught something or not?
Same thing....you would have to find a trainer for the class you are wanting to take. There are also Minimum number of Levels in Each Class posted on the Forum/Web Site to explain level rules.
You should MAKE SURE you have some Lore Skill Points. It is a very important Skill. You should also take the Martial Feat as it will be needed to harvest Ores and Wood for crafting.

In General a Lore of 10 should be enough for most things. For purposes of the ORS Crafting System a Lore Skill of 20 is the maximum you would ever need......so going above this would be for gaming purposes beyond the ORS.
Enchanting will allow you add properties to your gear to help you survive longer while moving about the world.
Like adding Fire Damage to a Weapon or Adding Dodge AC to your Boots.
The actual process is quite simple really. The combinations of possibilities are virtually endless though.

Have a look at the Book of Enchanting in the Library. The main focus to Enchant is Lore Skill or Spellcraft Skill. So having enough of it will make Enchanting much more successful....and later...guaranteed. Remember....Know How not Practice is how this crafting works.
You bet it is good. The best actually. Well worth the donation of skill points to very valuable skills.
Smelting Ore for example is handy.
Many reasons. The main reason is that smelted bars of metal are more valuable generally than plain ore. You can make a substantial amount of coin if you are diligent about your work.
Yes. You also gain XP and Coin for ore too but the bars are usually more valuable.

Yes of course. Many, many things. You should go to the library to have a look at the books......you can purchase the books as well....also in the library. Crafting stuff takes Know How.....not practice.
Not here no. You either know Crafting or you do not. Crafting uses your Armor and/or Weapon Crafting skills to make all sorts of things.
Contracts and Bounties is your way to do all sorts of repeatable duties around the realms.
This also depends a lot on the type of item. You will have to experiment a bit to get a good feel for this.
True. Also keep in mind that Contracts and Bounties on the same item can be more or less in different places.
Yes, you are correct. Also prices can be seasonal too.
Yes. This keeps things very interesting for players.
The point here is to communicate with other players of Trade Values in various parts of the world. Much like Dynamic Economies.
Not really. Quests are something different.
There are 2 types of questing here. The first being repeatable normal activities and the other being special purpose.
This is both varied and dynamic. There are people everywhere providing services to all people in Anvarath.
Merchants, guild halls leaders, sheriffs, and even a notice board are sources.
Sure. Squash, Silk Glands, Rat Ears, Goblin heads, and Ant Mandibles are all types.
Not at all. Ore and Wood and gems and all sorts of things you simply collect in nature.
Yes. Usually found at an Apothecary Merchant.
Yes it is. And it all depends upon you.

Bonuses (Added to Your Lore Skill):  Example => Dwarven Barabarian with 8 Lore Skill     Lore +8 + Racial +5 + Class +2 = +15
NOTE: Class is the PRIMARY Class ONLY!!

- Fighter +2

NOTE: Class is the PRIMARY Class ONLY!! 
- Elf +2
- Halfling +2
- Half Elf +1
- Druid +5
- Ranger +5
Prospecting is searching out what you think may be a Harvestable resource.

Ore...herbs.....and many more. As you adventure you will see things on the ground or around you that you think may be something you could harvest. Then you simply Prospect For Resources from this ORM. If it is a Resource AND you have enough skill.....then it will become available.

Experience and training. Some flowers for example may look exactly the same but they may be of a variety not useful for Herbs. When you Propect them you will know better if they are Herbs or not. This includes Fruit Trees....Mushrooms....many many more.
Indeed. You hit the nail on the head.
You have searched a 5m radius for resources you can harvest.

Paladins have the "detect evil" capability. Using the ability will reveal all evil creatures (both PC and PC) to the player. And, as absurd as this may seem, Neutral and Good creatures are *not* detected by the Detect Evil capability. :D

There is a 30 minute recharge period from your last use of the ability (independent of rest timer). After the 30 minutes, you are given an additional 3 charges.

The ranger's tracking ability reveals a multitude of information about creatures in a sphere of a radius dependant on the player's ranger level. The amount of information, the accuracy of the information, and the number of creatures the ranger can obtain information about from tracks depend on the player's ranger level. Creatures that are hiding (not spawned yet) will not reveal information; this facet of the tracking ability can simply be dismissed IC as the possiblity of creature "encampments", a creature dwelling where the residents therein do not move far from the area of habitation.

Inspecting a potential mark reveals detailed information about the rogue's target. The amount and type of information given depends on various statistics of the user of the ability, as well as the statistics of the target. General information concerning the stats of the rogue vs the stats of the target are among the pieces of information given.

Scrying allows a mage under the effect of the Clairvoyance/Clairaudience spell to remotely spy on any player character in the module, regardless of their location. The duration of the scrying is dependant on the level of the caster, though it is not extremely long. The person being watched has a chance to sense the intrusion (the 'being watched' feeling), though he will not be able to make out the person's name or current location IC or OOC.

The duration of the scrying is dependant on the level of the caster, though it is not extremely long. The person being watched has a chance to sense the intrusion (the 'being watched' feeling), though he will not be able to make out the person's name or current location IC or OOC.

-Communion with nature, may result in:
  -Minor help (common)
  -Help         (occasionally)
  -Natural Aid      (scarce)
  -Phenomenon (extremely rare!)

Results are not as per the spells of the same name.
The communion requires 15 seconds of absolute concentration, and may be performed once every 30 minutes. The effects of the help are typically relatively short. 

The 30 minute timer for this ability is independent of the module's rest timer.

-Plea for divine help, may result in:
  -Minor Blessing (common)
  -Blessing          (occasionally)
  -Aid                   (scarce)
  -Miracle            (extremely rare!)

Results are not as per the spells of the same name.
The plea requires 15 seconds of absolute concentration, and may be performed once every 30 minutes. The effects of the blessings are typically relatively short. 

There is a 30 minute recharge period from your last use of the ability (independent of rest timer).
